SI 370 - Homework #3: Applied Statistics¶

Background¶

This homework assignment focuses on data from the World Happiness Report.

The World Happiness Report is a landmark survey of the state of global happiness. The first report was published in 2012, the second in 2013, the third in 2015, and the fourth in the 2016 Update. The World Happiness 2017, which ranks 155 countries by their happiness levels, was released at the United Nations at an event celebrating International Day of Happiness on March 20th. The report continues to gain global recognition as governments, organizations and civil society increasingly use happiness indicators to inform their policy-making decisions. Leading experts across fields – economics, psychology, survey analysis, national statistics, health, public policy and more – describe how measurements of well-being can be used effectively to assess the progress of nations. The reports review the state of happiness in the world today and show how the new science of happiness explains personal and national variations in happiness.

We will be using data from the 2016 report.

Your main task in this assignment is to explore the data using the data manipulation, analysis, visualization, and applied statistical methods we covered in class as well as those in the assigned readings.

Q1: What are the top 5 correlation coefficients among "Happiness Score", Economy, Family, Health, Freedom, Trust, and Generosity? Provide a visualization as well as a written statement of your findings. (5 points)

In [261]:
narrowed = happiness[['Happiness Score','Economy (GDP per Capita)', 'Family', 'Health (Life Expectancy)', 'Freedom', 'Trust (Government Corruption)', 'Generosity']]
corr = narrowed.corr()
corr_pairs = corr.unstack()
sort_corr = pd.DataFrame(corr_pairs.sort_values())
sort_corr['absolute_corr'] = abs(sort_corr[0])
sort_corr = sort_corr.reset_index()
sort_corr = sort_corr.rename(columns={'level_0': 'var_1', 'level_1': 'var_2', 0:'Correlation'})
sort_corr = sort_corr.sort_values(by=['absolute_corr'], ascending=False)
sort_corr = sort_corr[sort_corr['absolute_corr'] != 1]
sort_corr = sort_corr.drop_duplicates(subset=['absolute_corr'])
sort_corr = sort_corr.rename(columns={'absolute_corr': 'Absolute Corr.'})
sort_corr.head()

             'Freedom','Trust (Government Corruption)','Generosity']

for x in relations:
    sns.jointplot("Happiness Score", x, data=happiness, kind='reg', color='g')
  • We can see that as family contributes more to the happiness scores the scores tend to increase as well.
  • For economy we see a steeper slope where there is a positive relationship as well. Therefore as economy increase so does happiness score.
  • We see a similar trend for health, where a postivie relationship is displayed.
  • The relationship between freedom and happiness scores tends to be a little different. Although the regression line is postive there appears to be a large amount of data scattered far from the line. This infers that there is not a very strong relation between these two variables.
  • Trust and happiness seem to also have a week, but still positive, relationship. There appears to be several high outliers and not an even distribution above and below the regression line.
  • Lastly we have generosity and happiness showing barely any relation. The regression line indicates a very small slope, indicating that there is not much correlation between generosity and happiness scores.

Q3: Does there appear to be an interaction between region and happiness quartile? (5 points)

Create a new variable that represents which quartile each country's happiness score is in. For example, the first 39 or 40 countries are in the 4th happiness quartile (it's up to you to decide exactly how to divide the countries into happiness quartiles).

(Hint: contingency tables, mosaic plots, and chi-square may be useful here).

In [265]:
#creates a new column that sorts the rows into quartiles
def Quartile(row):

    if row.name <= 39:
        return 'Q1'
    elif row.name  <= 78:
        return 'Q2'
    elif row.name  <= 117:
        return 'Q3'
    else:
        return 'Q4'
   
happiness['Quartile'] = happiness.apply (lambda row: Quartile(row), axis=1)
